If `(text != null &amp;&amp; text.contains(&quot;word&quot;))` never gets true, then it might be that no stored text run in the Word document fully contains the text &quot;word&quot;. Word is very special in splitting text in text runs. Not only formatting leads to split text runs. Also spell checker splits text in different text runs to mark errors. And sometimes Word is just crazy in how it splits text in text runs. So it can be that the text &quot;word&quot; is stored so: `&lt;r&gt;w&lt;/r&lt;r&gt;ord&lt;/r&gt;`.

To overcome those issues, [TextSegment](https://poi.apache.org/apidocs/dev/org/apache/poi/xwpf/usermodel/TextSegment.html) was introduced in Apache POI. It can be got via [XWPFParagraph.searchText](https://poi.apache.org/apidocs/dev/org/apache/poi/xwpf/usermodel/XWPFParagraph.html#searchText-java.lang.String-org.apache.poi.xwpf.usermodel.PositionInParagraph-).

